description:
Bug 38131ajc needs -d option to correctly compile classes from subpackage. I am using ajc 1.1rc1. This is a regression since rc1 and a deviation from javac. I am guessing this may have something to do with a change in the underlying Eclipse compiler.

To reproduce the issue, follow these steps:

1. Create a class in a subpackage like this:

   package subpackage;

   public class Test {

       public static void main(String[] args) {
           System.out.println("Hello");
       }
   }

2. Compile the class using the following command: ajc -d . subpackage\Test.java

Expected Behavior:

After compiling, only the class file should be created under the existing "subpackage" directory.

Observed Behavior:

Instead, a new directory named "subpackage" is created under the existing "subpackage" directory.

This behavior is not consistent with javac.

This is not a critical issue, but it should be addressed to maintain consistency.
